summary: This is an email from an FBI NYO CART Coordinator/Senior Forensic Examiner to an unspecified recipient regarding the processing and transfer of electronic evidence (phones, laptops, desktops) in an investigation, likely related to the Epstein case. The document is heavily redacted and marked as subject to a protective order.

persons.name: NYO CART Coordinator Senior Forensic Examiner
persons.context: The sender of the email, discussing the processing and transfer of electronic evidence items like phones, laptops, and desktops.

keyFacts: The document is an email dated July 14, 2020, concerning the forensic processing of electronic evidence.
The evidence mentioned includes phones, at least one laptop, and two desktops, indicating a significant digital evidence collection.
The sender, an FBI forensic examiner, notes that most items are being transferred to the Southern District of New York (SDNY).
The document is heavily redacted and explicitly subject to a protective order covering specific paragraphs (7, 8, 9, 10, 15, and 17).
The email discusses logistical challenges in re-processing and re-working data, suggesting an active phase of evidence handling in the investigation.
